b'This is wonderful, but not enough. Please be safe out there. Get vaccinated for yourself and your neighbors. And let\xe2\x80\x99s enjoy our concerts in safety and good health!!'

b'We have the tools to fix this. The vaccines really work and have saved so many lives. So grateful to all the scientists who worked so hard on this!  We went from peaking at several thousand deaths a day to a few hundred a day in the US.'

b'The only reason we could even plan this tour was because of how many of our neighbors got vaccinated. Cases, hospitalizations and deaths went down dramatically in highly vaccinated areas. But far too many areas haven\xe2\x80\x99t had enough shots and the Delta variant is running rampant.'
b'Being unvaccinated and/or unmasked at a large indoor gathering is like literally begging to get COVID. Please don\xe2\x80\x99t do that to yourself, your family or your neighbors.'

b'If you plan to be in a large group of people (like hopefully our concert!) in October, you have plenty of time to get fully vaccinated before you come.  Every city and venue will have different rules, but we don\xe2\x80\x99t need the mayor or governor to tell us what\xe2\x80\x99s safe.'

b'I\xe2\x80\x99ve got your Father\xe2\x80\x99s Day plans covered. Join my family and friends on Sunday, June 21st for #JohnLegendFathersDay at 8|7c on @ABCNetwork! #BiggerLove https://t.co/HsDHI2Gaou'
b'A week from today, on June 19, I invite you to experience a #BiggerLove.'

b'I debuted in 2004 with an album called Get Lifted.  And now, as we enter the summer of 2020, I hope this new album can get you lifted again, fill your hearts with love and inspiration, give you something to dance to, something to hold hands to, something to make love to.'

b'I\xe2\x80\x99m under no illusion that music can save the world or solve the world\xe2\x80\x99s problems, but I\xe2\x80\x99ve always turned to music to help me through tough times and I know many of you have done the same.  That\xe2\x80\x99s why I couldn\xe2\x80\x99t wait to release this album to the world.'

b'But It\xe2\x80\x99s important for us to continue to show the world the fullness of what it is to be black & human. Through our art, we are able to do that. This album is a celebration of love, joy, sensuality, hope, & resilience, the things that make our culture so beautiful & influential.'
b'Lately, the images of black people in the media have been showing us with knees on our necks, in mourning, or expressing our collective outrage.  We feel all those emotions.'

b'All of these songs were created prior to the world being rocked by a pandemic, prior to the latest police killings in the U.S. that sent so many to the streets in protest.  During these painful times, some of us may wonder if it\xe2\x80\x99s ok to laugh or dance or be romantic.'
b'The songs are inspired by the loves of my life:  my wife, my family and the rich tradition of black music that has made me the artist I am.'

b'This project has been a labor of love for me, something I\xe2\x80\x99ve spent over a year conceiving and creating.  I poured my heart and soul into these songs and collaborated with some incredibly gifted co-writers, producers and musicians.'

b'I\xe2\x80\x99m so excited to introduce my new album #BiggerLove to the world.  Here\xe2\x80\x99s the album cover painted by brilliant artist Charly Palmer.  Check out the track list, including my amazing featured guests. https://t.co/nWu6Y2JhRH'

b'Everyone was saying $15 minimum wage and Medicare for All and gay marriage were also unrealistic and ridiculous but activists moved the conversation and pushed politicians toward progress'

b"It's not the job of grass roots activists on the left to craft political messaging for mainstream democratic candidates. I'm almost 100% sure Biden won't be tweeting #DefundThePolice.  It's the job of activists to push these politicians toward meaningful change."

b'"defund" is the word because it says we\'re taking away some funding from one budget item and moving it to higher priorities. "reform" or "retrain" does not at all suggest the same thing. We\'ve been supposedly doing the latter for decades'

b"This doesn't mean there will be no police; it means there should be significantly fewer police and more professionals of other types with expertise in their fields, whether it's social work, health care, conflict resolution, drug treatment, etc"

b'Whenever there are budget cuts, those "softer" services are on the chopping block first.  And, since we know we\'re not solving the underlying problems, we figure we better keep a huge police force to contain them.  Let\'s resolve to do differently.  Let\'s imagine a healthier world'

b'And that choice comes at a cost. We defund housing support, health care, education and child care, the arts, drug treatment, community centers, all sorts of services that would actually reduce the problems that we ask the police to surveil and contain'

b'Police funding takes up a huge portion of our local budgets. Budgets are moral documents which spell out in black and white what our priorities are. We have finite amounts of money to spend and right now we spend far too much on policing'

b'Some intentionally want to cast the argument in extremes like that so they can score political points. But I ask that those of you who are reasonable and actually care about making this country healthy and safe for all people engage with the thoughtful arguments in this piece'

b'I know this word "defund" has caused some controversy, even from some who are inclined to agree with a lot of the underlying arguments. Some hear that word and envision The Purge, some dystopian descent into anarchy'

b'Bill Withers and I when we celebrated his induction into the Rock & Roll Hall of Fame. He hadn\'t sung in public for many years but he joined me and Stevie for "Lean on Me". Thank you for the inspiration and the\xe2\x80\xa6 https://t.co/54zLYjkLjj'

b'The way he communicated it was via a long, funny email that I later discovered was a trademark of his.  I always looked forward to hearing from him. He always had a great story for me, told with charm and wit and humor.  What a special human being'

b'Bill and I became friends after he saw  this YouTube clip.  His friend Bill Russell (yes that Bill Russell) called him up and told him to check it out.  Then he emailed someone who then emailed my manager who then forwarded it to me. He loved our version. My year was made.'

b"This song will always mean so much to me. Our performances of it were always epic and emotional.  Some of my favorite of my entire musical life.  Captain Kirk's guitar solo was so powerful and dynamic and unpredictable.  The first time I ever cried while cutting a vocal was this https://t.co/McnOGu8vzH"

b"Mourning the loss of my friend and inspiration, Bill Withers.  He was such an incredible songwriter and storyteller.  I'm so glad he shared his gift with the world.  Life wouldn't be the same without him."

b'@pmtisariddle @secupp If I ever run for office, I certainly will.  Still waiting for POTUS\'s "audit" to be over, I assume?'
b'@secupp Democracy is most certainly messy and imperfect but depending on the largesse and pet interests of unaccountable oligarchs is a far worse option.'
b'@secupp *unaccountable'
b"@secupp Trust has to be earned. But at least the people get to vote on politicians every 2-6 years. It'd be nice if those elections were free of unaccounted billionaires tipping the scale."
b"@secupp And I'm pretty sure people have been criticizing him pretty loudly for at least the past decade."

b"@secupp It may not matter, honestly.  But I think a lot of these guys care about their legacy. Maybe the ones who are still alive will see this and do better. Maybe they'll at least attempt to do more good than harm in the world."

b'@secupp How many Medicaid expansion refusers did he fund? How many politicians who wanted to strip healthcare from millions did he fund?  He could have invested his money in making healthcare more accessible to the poor and working class.  He did the opposite.'

b"@secupp At least politicians have to answer to the people. At least when there aren't billionaires actively funding anti-democratic efforts like voter suppression and gerrymandering. Thanks again, Koch Brothers."

b"@secupp I think we'll never agree on the role of government.  You'll always prefer less than I do. I get that. But I'd rather rely on democratically-elected officials than an unaccountable billionaire to set priorities and fund public goods."

b"@JonTrotterEsq @secupp We can all debate the moral implications of everyone's political acts.  Part of your opinion will be based on your own priorities and values.  But let's at least be clear-eyed and examine the facts of what he advocated for and the real-life effects of the policies he championed."
b'@secupp When you work so hard to avoid paying taxes that could go to fund things like education, the arts and infrastructure, spare me the celebration of your donation to the arts.'

b"@secupp For instance, when you spend so much to support politicians who want to strip health insurance from people, IDGAF about the money you spend on cancer research.  People without health insurance can't access that amazing research anyway."
b"@secupp I don't celebrate his death. But I most certainly don't celebrate his life."

b"@secupp He spent a decent amount fighting for crim justice reform too.  It's a cause I care about deeply.  People are complicated.  But I have to say that the net effect of the Koch brothers' activism is highly negative and I don't think it's that close of a call."
b"@secupp It's not a lack of attention I'm concerned about. It's active attention towards destructive political aims."
